Heres the ELI5


08 May 2017 14:59






For those who have never been to an IKEA, here's how the store works:

The store invites you upstairs into a giant warehouse-sized showroom. Here, you are shown a meandering path that twists and turns its way through room idea after room idea of IKEA furniture. Bedrooms, living rooms, dining rooms, kitchens, etc., all done in IKEA furniture. As you can imagine, it's easy to get lost in a space like this. About halfway through your trek, you come across a food court where you can stop, rest, and provision before continuing your odyssey through bookcases, coffee tables, and more. The Swedish meatballs are a perennial staple and very popular.

All in all, it's easy to lose an hour or two before you complete your journey and head back to the ground level, where you can finally choose the actual items you were looking for in a much more open warehouse area.

So, yes, becoming lost in a veritable sea of DIY furniture is the typical IKEA experience.





